title: Grateful Dead Live at Shoreline Amphitheatre on 1987-10-02
lineage: Cassette Master (Tascam 122mkII) -> Apogee MiniMe (24bit/48k) ->Samplitude Professional v9.02 -> FLAC/16
description:
Set 1

Cold Rain & Snow, Little Red Rooster, Stagger Lee, Me & My Uncle-> Mexicali Blues, Row Jimmy, Far From Me, Let It Grow

Set 2

China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Women Are Smarter, Ship of Fools, Truckin'-> Drums, Jam-> The Wheel-> Gimme Some Lovin'-> All Along The Watchtower, E: Black Muddy River

reviews.review_text: Credit due Let's give credit where credit is do. Another beauty of an upgraded show from CM for the masses to enjoy. Thank you for all the time you've invested into the shows on the Archives. The sound is pretty darn good for such a huge open air amphitheatre.

fun stuff The people reviewing this show in other filesets are funny. This China Rider is a snoozer? None of them even noticed Bobby's guitar isn't working until halfway through the transition jam so I'm not sure how closely anyone was listening. Phil and Jerry make up for it by blazing their way through it. Phil in particular goes off. The Women is also a nice version though Brent kinda biffs his solo. As noted by others the Let It Grow is serious biznis.

First 3 songs were released in pro shot video/remastered audio on the DVD box set bonus disk

Getting their open
The venue had been designed with the Dead in mind (which is why it resembles a Lightning Skull from above), and they were the planned openers. But Garcia's coma meant the slot went to Frampton/Nicks. They did go on to play it 39 times - once it was rebuilt for the methane leaks from the landfill below (up on the lawn section, dropped cigarettes would ignite flames). The canvas top was once the world's largest. The next show is better known, but this has a must-hear sequence, part of a second set with several fine moments. First Set. An average set, GOGD, no aces, no trainwrecks, ranging from Bobby Slide Practice™ in Rooster, to a wonderful Me & My Uncle (though Bobby's guitar is buried here). Second Set. China Cat is not unusual (Bobby's guitar is thin on the SBDs but better on the AUDs and the DVD), but Rider is astonishing in places. The energy gained is credit used for a fantastic Dewiminna. Jer is the strongest player but it's a boscage of spirals when you wade in. The year's best, capping a must-hear sequence. Jer is still fine, but a few others are not on top of it for Ship. There is a superb beam episode during a big Drums>Space excursion. There are better versions of Watchtower from the era (8/18), but one this good is always welcome. Dough Knees is nice in this slot, though this one is too tentative. Black Muddy is '87's standard encore [21 times]. 1st Set:  C+ 2nd Set: B- Overall = 3¼ stars Highlights: I Know You Rider - astonishing in places Man Smart (Woman Smarter) - caps a surprising sequence Drums - great beam episode Space - big excursion SOURCES: The miller_121960 updates and fixes the pitch of the miller_83905. The 42580_sbd_bm_miller is the same, with slightly less quality. There's a great AUD (mk41_oade_jacobs_miller_clugston) and a fine MTX (43553_mtx_tobin). The 143555.5-1_tobin is a 5.1 surround folded back to stereo. The first three of the second set are in the All the Years Combine DVD box. The show is up on YouTube.

The boys’ Shoreline debut. I find that my favorite mid-’80s shows tend to be from East Coast venues. In years like 1987, the Grateful Dead’s sound was so feral and loose that they almost needed the charged up pressure of the Spectrum, Centrum, MSG, or the Hartford Civic Center, just to tighten things up a smidge and keep those sloshy jams from completely spilling off the rails.

When they brought that loose, delightful mid-’80s slop to a venue as inherently loose as Shoreline, some tunes were bound to end up a little frazzled. But as a whole, this is an exciting and well-executed Shoreline debut for the band that would basically stake their flag in the place and claim it as their home turf forevermore. Highlights include a ferocious Little Red Rooster, hazy Row Jimmy, and a buoyant China > Rider.

It’s rough around the edges at times. Far From Me sees Jerry and Bob comically croaking along, while Brent proves himself the real singer of the group (an assertion Jerry himself made back in the day with open candor). It’s a squirrely ‘80s show, but sometimes that’s exactly what you need. There’s a very positive vibe clinging to this performance. The Grateful Dead were riding high, thanks to the enormous momentum of Jerry coming back from the brink, the release of In the Dark, the tour with Dylan, and a great fall tour. It’s no wonder that this first show of theirs at the venue famously shaped like a stealie is just one more in a long line of 1987 successes.

This splendid SBD is easy on the ears for those on the go, but the band’s official YouTube channel has this one available in multi-cam pro-shot video as well!
